    <!-- FAQ -->
    <div class="faq-section">
      <h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>

      <div class="faq-item">
        <button class="faq-q">Is gas or electric oven cheaper to run for a bakery in India? <span class="icon">+</span></button>
        <div class="faq-a">LPG gas is the cheapest fuel to run a bakery oven in India for medium and large operations, typically costing 40–55% less than electricity. However, PNG (piped natural gas) can actually be more expensive than electricity in some cities like Mumbai. At small scale (4-tray oven, 6 hours/day), the savings from gas are partially offset by higher installation costs, so the advantage is smaller. At large scale (full-rack rotary oven, 16 hours/day), LPG gas can save over ₹10 lakh per year vs electricity.</div>
      </div>

      <div class="faq-item">
        <button class="faq-q">Can I convert an electric oven to gas or vice versa? <span class="icon">+</span></button>
        <div class="faq-a">No — gas and electric ovens are fundamentally different designs with different heating systems, safety components, and airflow management. You cannot convert one to the other. If you need to switch, you must buy a new oven. Some manufacturers do make the same oven model in both gas and electric versions, so if you think you might switch fuel types in the future, consider brands that offer both.</div>
      </div>

      <div class="faq-item">
        <button class="faq-q">Which is safer — a gas or electric bakery oven? <span class="icon">+</span></button>
        <div class="faq-a">Electric ovens are inherently safer — there is no combustion, no risk of gas leaks, and no flame. Gas ovens can be very safe when properly installed with gas detectors, automatic shut-off valves, and adequate ventilation, but they carry an inherent fire and explosion risk if any of these safety systems fail or are absent. For kitchens in enclosed commercial complexes, hospitals, schools, or where the building management restricts gas use, electric is the required choice.</div>
      </div>

      <div class="faq-item">
        <button class="faq-q">Is PNG or LPG better for a bakery oven in India? <span class="icon">+</span></button>
        <div class="faq-a">LPG is cheaper per unit of heat produced than PNG in most Indian cities. However, PNG is more convenient — you never run out mid-bake, there's no cylinder logistics, and the installation is cleaner. If you're in a city with good PNG coverage and the rate is below ₹50/SCM (like Delhi at ~₹48), PNG is an excellent choice. If your city's PNG rate is above ₹58/SCM, LPG cylinders may actually be cheaper despite the logistical overhead.</div>
      </div>

      <div class="faq-item">
        <button class="faq-q">Do gas ovens bake better bread than electric ovens? <span class="icon">+</span></button>
        <div class="faq-a">For most bread types — especially high-volume production of pav, dinner rolls, and white loaves — gas deck or rotary ovens produce excellent results and the slight humidity from combustion is beneficial. For artisan sourdough or hearth breads, a stone-deck gas oven with steam injection is arguably the gold standard. However, for very temperature-sensitive breads (like brioche or enriched doughs that need precise heat control), an electric oven with programmable zones can give more consistent results. Most large Indian bakeries use gas rotary ovens for bread with no issues.</div>
      </div>

      <div class="faq-item">
        <button class="faq-q">What is the installation cost for a commercial gas oven in India? <span class="icon">+</span></button>
        <div class="faq-a">Commercial gas oven installation in India typically costs ₹25,000 – ₹60,000 for an LPG cylinder bank setup, or ₹30,000 – ₹70,000 for a PNG connection. This includes the manifold/regulator, gas pipework, gas detector, and safety shut-off valve. These costs are higher than electric oven installation (₹8,000 – ₹20,000) but are offset by lower running costs over time.</div>
      </div>

      <div class="faq-item">
        <button class="faq-q">Which cities in India have PNG for commercial bakeries? <span class="icon">+</span></button>
        <div class="faq-a">PNG is well-established in Delhi NCR (IGL), Mumbai and Pune (MGL), Gujarat cities like Ahmedabad, Surat and Vadodara (GSPC/Gujarat Gas), and Hyderabad (Bhagyanagar Gas). It has moderate coverage in Kolkata, Lucknow, Kanpur, Indore, and Bhopal. Coverage in Bangalore and Chennai remains limited in 2026, though expanding. Most smaller cities and rural areas rely on LPG cylinders. Check with your local city gas distribution company for the current coverage map in your area.</div>
      </div>
    </div>

